Activated sludge models provide a mechanistic basis for wastewater-process analysis, but their coupled non-linear kinetics limit the practical use of transparent surrogates for rapid design, analysis, and optimization. Standard machine-learning surrogates can improve predictive efficiency, yet they generally do not guarantee two basic physical requirements of steady-state activated sludge systems: exact conservation of the stoichiometrically implied material inventories and componentwise non-negativity of the predicted ASM state. This article develops Invariant-Constrained Second-Order Regression (ICSOR), an interpretable surrogate framework that addresses both requirements within a single steady-state formulation. ICSOR uses a partitioned second-order feature map over operational variables and influent ASM components, a learned coupled component-space driver, and deterministic recursive coupled-QP estimation to retain a transparent coefficient structure. At deployment, the method applies a hierarchical correction sequence consisting of a raw coupled prediction, an affine invariant restoration, and a final linear program that enforces exact conservation and non-negativity simultaneously. Because the model is formulated directly in ASM component space, reported effluent composites are obtained only through an external composition map after deployment. The study is developed for a standalone continuous stirred tank reactor and is positioned for comparison against unconstrained surrogate baselines to assess whether physically admissible predictions can be obtained without sacrificing interpretability or competitive predictive performance.
